## Notification mechanisms operators see

<!-- PROJECT: Name each user-visible surface where the tool reports
its limitations.  Operators need to be able to grep / screenshot /
cite these.  Every banner / panel / comment should be reachable from
this section. -->

The UI surfaces every place the `<tool>` can't faithfully `<perform
the operation>`.  Each surface is named so operators can grep the
rendered output or screen-grab the panel.

### A. Capability matrix "Unsupported" / "Lossy" panels

The `<process / migrate>` page renders three lists: Supported / Lossy
/ Unsupported.  See per-`<COMPONENT>` tables above.

### B. `<Tier-3 / opaque section detection>` banner

When a source `<COMPONENT>` parses an input that contains stanzas it
deliberately drops, the parser's per-`<COMPONENT>` heuristic detector
populates `<CORE_ABSTRACTION>.dropped_<tier3>_sections` with the
matching headers.  The `<UI page>` renders these as a warning banner:

> ⚠ `<Tier-3 / opaque>` sections detected in source — The source
> contains N section(s) this tool does not translate (`<example
> categories>`).  These will NOT appear in the rendered output.
> Operator must apply them manually on the target.

### C. Render-time review comments

When a render path can't faithfully emit a piece of `<CORE_ABSTRACTION>`
state, it emits a comment in the target's native syntax instead of
guessing or silently dropping.  Operators searching for `review:` in
rendered output find every such site.

* **`<EXAMPLE: Hash-portability policy>`** — when a `<sensitive
  field>` cannot be re-used on the target, emits a vendor-correct
  comment instead of leaking the literal value.
* `<...>`

### D. Validation severity (`ok` / `warn` / `block`)

Every `<job>` carries a validation severity computed from the target's
capability matrix vs. the populated `<CORE_ABSTRACTION>` fields:

* `ok` — every populated field maps to a `supported` xpath on the
  target.
* `warn` — at least one field hits a `lossy` xpath; render proceeds.
* `block` — at least one field hits an `unsupported` xpath; the
  job's status flips to `partial` (rendered output exists but should
  be reviewed before deploy).

`<job>` status reaches `failed` only when a stage actually raises;
validation alone never fails the job.

